  "prompt": "What is input tax credit and output tax credit?",
  "response": "Input Tax Credit (ITC) and Output Tax Credit are important concepts in taxation, particularly in Goods and Services Tax (GST) systems:\n\nInput Tax Credit (ITC):\n1. Definition\n- Credit of tax paid on purchases/inputs used in business\n- Allows businesses to offset taxes already paid on inputs against taxes on output supplies\n\n2. Key Features\n- Reduces overall tax liability\n- Prevents cascading of taxes\n- Applies to goods and services used in business operations\n- Helps maintain tax compliance and reduce tax burden\n\nOutput Tax Credit:\n1. Definition\n- Tax collected on sales/output of goods and services\n- Amount of tax charged to customers when selling goods or services\n\n2. Key Characteristics\n- Calculated based on sale price and applicable tax rate\n- Reported in sales tax returns\n- Used to calculate net tax liability\n- Includes tax collected from customers\n\nDifferences:\n- Input Tax Credit is tax paid on purchases\n- Output Tax Credit is tax collected on sales\n- ITC reduces tax liability, while output tax represents tax collected\n\nConditions for ITC:\n- Valid tax invoice\n- Goods/services used for business purposes\n- Payment made to supplier\n- Tax returns filed correctly\n\nBoth concepts are crucial in modern taxation systems to ensure transparent and efficient tax collection.",
